**Title:** How to Push a Python Project to GitHub from VS Code (Without Signing In)

---

## Step-by-Step Guide

### 1. Open Your Project in VS Code
- Open your local Python project folder using Visual Studio Code.

### 2. Initialize Git
Open the terminal in VS Code and run:

```bash
git init
```

This will turn your project folder into a Git repository.

### 3. Configure Git (If Needed)
Set your username and email for Git commits:

```bash
git config --global user.name "YourUsername"
git config --global user.email "youremail@example.com"
```

### 4. Stage Your Files
Add all project files to Git's staging area:

```bash
git add .
```

### 5. Commit Your Changes
Create your first commit:

```bash
git commit -m "First commit"
```

### 6. Create a Repository on GitHub
- Go to [GitHub](https://github.com/) and create a new repository.
- Do NOT check the "Initialize this repository with a README" option.

### 7. Link Your Local Repository to GitHub
Add the remote URL (replace with your own repo URL):

```bash
git remote add origin https://github.com/yourusername/your-repo-name.git
```

### 8. (Optional) Pull Before Push
If there is any file already present on GitHub (like README), you must pull first:

```bash
git pull origin main --allow-unrelated-histories
```

### 9. Push Your Project to GitHub
Push your local commits to GitHub:

```bash
git push -u origin main
```

### 10. Authentication
When pushing or pulling, GitHub will prompt you for authentication:
- Enter your GitHub **username**.
- Instead of your password, enter your **Personal Access Token (PAT)**.

**Note:** GitHub no longer accepts account passwords for authentication; you must use a PAT.

